Business Scenario Lab

This project facilitates the synchronization of master patient records across different healthcare providers. It is important to have consistent patient information across these multiple providers so that patients can receive consistent care. For that to occur, their personal and medical information must be shared. Additionally, updates to the patient record must flow across the providers to maintain accuracy and currency.

The NextGate web service is provided for testing.

Goals

  • Build a RESTful CXF service that receives the patient record and validates it

  • Publish the XML to a queue

  • Receive the message from the message queue and invoke the back-end web service

  • Respond with an acknowledgment to the client using the Done transformer in the use case document

Grading Criteria

The grading criteria for this lab is based on the following criteria. A grade of 20 points or higher is required for passing.

  • Build out the routes in all of the subprojects (5 points)

  • Include clear instructions about how to build and run the assignment (5 points)

  • Include individual subprojects that build cleanly and whose JUnit tests run without errors (10 points)

  • Build out a significant set of tests for the scenario or create a significant dataset and testing using mvn camel:run (10 points)

  • Include a concise explanation of the design choices made and areas for improvement (10 points)

1. Import Lab Project and Build Projects

  1. In Red Hat® Developer Studio, switch to the Git perspective.

  2. Click the icon at the top to clone a Git repository and add the clone to the view.

  3. In the URI text box, copy and paste the following: 

    https://github.com/gpe-mw-training/experienced-integration-labs.git

  4. Switch to Project Explorer for the Fuse Integration perspective.

  5. Select File → Import → Maven → Existing Maven Projects, and then click Next to import core and its parent project:

    Homework Project

  6. Click the Project Explorer tab and expand the Inbound project node:

    Application Structure

  7. Examine the subfolders of the core folder that appear in the expanded view, where you develop the parts of this use case:

    • artifacts: WSDL and XSD files on which you base the project

    • inbound: Route or service that receives the patient payload

    • outbound: Route that publishes the XML payload to an AMQ queue

    • xlate: Route that marshalls the Java™ object to XML

  8. At the command line, build the parent project: 

    mvn clean install

  9. Build the artifacts project: 

    mvn clean install

    • Among other things, this generates the Java client/server stubs from the WSDL files.

2. Develop Inbound Application

2.1. Develop CXF REST Service

For this section, Red Hat recommends that you use a standard REST service CXF-RS. Alternately, you can use the Camel REST component.

For the design of the REST service, use the following guidelines:

  • Use Spring or Blueprint, either of which starts a RESTful service whose implementation creates a producer template and a call to a direct endpoint in Camel.

  • In blueprint.xml, create a bean, which is the REST service.

  • Implement the add, update, and search methods in the REST endpoint service.

  1. Use this REST service design to formulate a response to the client that indicates why the request failed.

  2. Validate the schema against the incoming payloads.

  3. Implement a Java class that is the REST endpoint.

    • The class creates a producer template and calls the direct route.

    • The direct route puts the message on AMQ and returns, allowing you to return an OK status to the client in the Java class.

  4. Use the JAXB marshaller to convert the Java payload to XML.

  5. Publish the XML message to the AMQ queue.

    • When the message is successfully published, a "Done" XML string is sent back to the client.

2.2. Develop JUnit Tests

  1. Develop a feature and a fabric profile.

  2. Test these using SoapUI or curl.

2.3. Build Inbound Project

  1. In a terminal shell, build the project: 

    mvn clean install

3. Develop and Build Xlate Application

3.1. Develop Xlate Application

  1. Develop the code to consume the Person XML message from the q.empi.deim.in ActiveMQ queue.

  2. Unmarshall the Person XML message to a Person Java object.

  3. Convert the Person object to an ExecuteMatchUpdate object (an operation on the web service), by writing your own TypeConverter with the convertTo method implemented, using these parameters:

    • Type: Type of object to which you want to convert

    • Exchange (input): An Exchange object with a getIn() and getBody() returning a Person object that you copy into the object

    • Object: Object to which you want to convert

  4. Marshall the ExecuteMatchUpdate object to an ExecuteMatchUpdate XML message.

  5. Publish the ExecuteMatchUpdate XML message to the q.empi.nextgate.out ActiveMQ queue.

3.2. Build Xlate Project

  1. In a terminal shell, build the project: 

    mvn clean install

4. Develop Outbound Application and Test

4.1. Develop Outbound Application

  1. Write code to consume a ExecuteMatchUpdate XML message from the q.empi.nextgate.out ActiveMQ queue.

  2. Unmarshal the ExecuteMatchUpdate XML message to an ExecuteMatchUpdate Java object

  3. Use the ExecuteMatchUpdate object to build the NextGate web service request and send to the NextGate web service.

    • This dispatches the request to the NextGate service URI (CXF_WS_ENDPOINT_URI).

    • The input is the WSDL for the web service.

4.2. Develop JUnit Tests

  1. Develop a feature and a fabric profile.

  2. Test these using SoapUI or curl.

4.3. Deploy Test Web Service in Apache Karaf

  1. Build the integration-test-server JAR in the services/integration-test-server folder.

    Example Commands
    % bin/karaf
>osgi:install mvn:com.customer.app/integration-test-server/1.0-SNAPSHOT
>osgi:install mvn:com.customer.app/artifacts/1.0-SNAPSHOT
>osgi:start [bundle-id for integration-test-server]
>osgi:start [bundle-id for artifacts]
>osgi:list

    • This project depends on the osgi:install mvn:com.customer.app/artifacts/1.0-SNAPSHOT local artifact.

      Tip

      Compile the core project to get this JAR.

4.4. Build Outbound Project

  1. In a terminal shell, build the project: 

    mvn clean install
